SIMPLE: prickle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prickle
<hw>Pric"kle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>pricele</ets>, <ets>pricle</ets>; akin to LG. <ets>prickel</ets>,
D. <ets>prikkel</ets>. See <er>Prick</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A little prick; a small, sharp point; a fine, sharp
process or projection, as from the skin of an animal, the bark of a
plant, etc.; a spine.</def> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of willow basket; -- a term still used in
some branches of trade.</def> <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A sieve of filberts, -- about fifty pounds.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prickle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prickle
<hw>Pric"kle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To prick slightly, as with
prickles, or fine, sharp points.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Felt a horror over me creep,⟦br⟧
<qex>Prickle</qex> skin, and catch my breath.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pricklefish</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Prickleback</ent>⟦br⟧
